<div class="markdown"><h1>Step 7: Perform Cross validation</h1><ul><li><p>Previously, we fit a model based on all of our observations and then asked if the resulting model made good <strong>"postdictions"</strong>.  This is a relatively weak test.</p></li><li><p>A stronger test would be to see if the model can make good <strong>predictions</strong> for new data.  </p></li><li><p>Often, acquiring new data is very time consuming/expensive.</p></li><li><p>This motivates a more powerful method for assessing models: <strong>cross validation (CV)</strong>.</p></li></ul><h2>Cross validation of a single model</h2><ul><li><p>Divide data into <strong>two subsets</strong> (e.g., 75% "training", 25% "validation")</p></li><li><p>Fit data ("train model") using only the <strong>training set</strong></p></li><li><p>Use resulting parameters to make predictions for <strong>validation set</strong></p></li><li><p>How well did the model do?  (evaluate "loss function")</p></li></ul><h2>Cross validation when considering multiple models</h2><ul><li><p>Divide data into <strong>three subsets</strong> (e.g., 60% "training", 20% "validation", 20% "test")</p></li><li><p>For each model you want to consider:</p><ul><li><p>Fit/Train using only data from training set</p></li><li><p>Validate using only data from validation set</p></li></ul></li><li><p>Pick which model you'll use for decissions/publication:</p></li><li><p>Evaluate predictions for <strong>test set</strong>.</p></li><li><p>Report results on test data.</p></li><li><p><strong>Avoid temptation</strong> to make further "improvements" at the point.</p></li></ul></div>
